        .cell.medium-8
          h3.color-purple.padding-top-1.strong THE CHALLENGE
          p Sub-Saharan Africa is acknowledged to be the critical development challenge of the 21st century. The per capita income in Sub-Saharan though has seen steady rise since the 90s (from $606 to $1554 in 2017 According to World Bank), Sub-Saharan Africa still lags behind other continents in the world by a large amount.

          p Underlying the low per capita income are high rates of unemployment or underemployment and low levels of productivity. Across the continent, nations are under pressure to provide employment opportunities especially for the youth. To enable growth, a number of preconditions have to be met, one of which is human capacity development.

          p Skills development needed to increase productivity and make economies more competitive is critical, but gets less attention. To provide sustainable growth for developing economies, Sub-Saharan nations need to look into providing training and economic opportunities for its teeming youths, which currently make up more than half of the population.

          p Strategies for skills development is varied and involves both short term and long term approaches to the problem. Besides affecting the performance of firms, skills constraints also hamper African countries’ capacity to manage the conditions required to foster rapid growth.

